4","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1124–1197":"1124–1197","1126–1175":"1126–1175","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1314":"1314","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","1265":"1265","1254":"1254","before 1175":"før 1175","before 1150":"før 1150","Ireland":"Irland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"},"nl":{"before 1175–1240":"vóór 1175–1240","1150–1226":"1150–1226","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1225–1314":"1225–1314","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1124–1197":"1124–1197","1126–1175":"1126–1175","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1314":"1314","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","1265":"1265","1254":"1254","before 1175":"vóór 1175","before 1150":"vóór 1150","Ireland":"Ierland","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"before 1175–1240":"before 1175–1240","1150–1226":"1150–1226","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1225–1314":"1225–1314","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1124–1197":"1124–1197","1126–1175":"1126–1175","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1314":"1314","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","1265":"1265","1254":"1254","before 1175":"before 1175","before 1150":"before 1150","Ireland":"Ireland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bermingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Sinead.","Irish (of English origin): variant of   Birmingham  . This form of the surname is found mainly in Ireland.","History: The Bermingham family take their surname from lands held at what is now a great city in the West Midlands of England, but it was brought to Ireland as early as the 12th century. The Norman baron Robert de Bermyngeham was a follower of Strongbow (see   Clare  ); his name is found on a number of Irish charters between 1175 and 1179. The family was also known as <i>Mac Fheorais</i> (see   Corish  ) in Ireland, named for Piers (Gaelic <i>Feoras</i>) de Bermyngeham, the father of Robert."],"variants":[{"name":"Birmingham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birmingham in the West Midlands. In Domesday Book the name is already found as <i>Bermingeham</i>, but it seems likely that it was originally <i>Beornmundingahām</i> ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the people of (<i>-inga-</i>) <i>Beornmund</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young man, warrior’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’. This surname is established in Ireland (see   Bermingham  )."]},{"name":"Corish","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of <i>Mac Fheorais</i> ‘son of Piers’. The name was borne by a Connacht family descended from Piers de Bermingham, second lord of Athenry in Galway (died <i>c.</i> 1309). Compare   Bermingham  .","shortened form of <i>Mac Muirghis</i> ‘son of <i>Maurice</i>’, a personal name introduced to Ireland by the Normans. Compare   Morrissey  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bermingham was born before 1175, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, his father, Robert de Bermingham, was 51 and his mother, Catherine de Valognes Valensis, was 48. He died in 1240, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1175–1240":"enne 1175–1240","1150–1226":"1150–1226","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1225–1314":"1225–1314","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1124–1197":"1124–1197","1126–1175":"1126–1175","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1314":"1314","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","1265":"1265","1254":"1254","before 1175":"enne 1175","before 1150":"enne 1150","Ireland":"Iirimaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Birmingham, Warwickshire,